  "prompt": "How was Ankara chosen to be the capital of Turkey?",
  "response": "Ankara was chosen as the capital of Turkey for several strategic and symbolic reasons, following the fall of the Ottoman Empire and during the establishment of the Republic of Turkey.\n\n1. **Strategic Location**: Ankara is located in the central part of Anatolia, which makes it geographically more secure and less vulnerable to enemy attacks compared to Istanbul, which is located on the coast. Its central position in the country also made it easier to administer the newly established republic.\n\n2. **Symbolism of a Fresh Start**: The move to Ankara represented a break from the Ottoman past and a step towards modernization and secular governance under Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk. Istanbul was deeply associated with the Ottoman Empire, and moving the capital symbolized a new beginning.\n\n3. **Role During the War of Independence**: During the Turkish War of Independence (1919\u20131923), Ankara served as the headquarters for the nationalist movement led by Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk. The city was already functioning as a de facto capital for the nationalists as it hosted the Grand National Assembly of Turkey.\n\n4. **Neutrality in Factional Struggles**: Unlike Istanbul, Ankara was not a stronghold of any particular faction vying for power. This made it a neutral ground free from the political entanglements and power struggles that characterized Istanbul.\n\n5. **Economic Considerations**: Being in the agrarian heartland of Turkey, Ankara offered a new economic focus away from the trade and commerce-dominated economy of Istanbul.\n\n6. **Modernization Goals**: Atat\u00fcrk and his followers sought to modernize Turkey, and relocating the capital was part of their efforts to reconstruct the country. They had the opportunity to design and construct a new city that aligned with their vision.\n\nIn 1923, when the Republic of Turkey was founded, Ankara was officially declared its capital. This decision was made formal by the Grand National Assembly due to these strategic, political, and symbolic reasons.",
